==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Enounce
<hw>E*nounce"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Enounced</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Enouncing</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F.
<ets>⟦eacute⟧noncer</ets>, L. <ets>enuntiare</ets>; <ets>e</ets> out +
<ets>nuntiare</ets> to announce, fr. <ets>nuntius</ets> messenger. See
<er>Nuncio</er>, and cf. <er>Enunciate</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
announce; to declare; to state, as a proposition or argument.</def>
<rj><au>Sir W. Hamilton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To utter; to articulate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The student should be able to <qex>enounce</qex> these [sounds]
independently.</q> <rj><qau>A. M. Bell.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Enouncement</ent>⟦br⟧
